data.title: imurica & Oral B - Reporting figures discussion

categories.summary: The seller argues that imurica EMEA's global perspective and depth of data are superior to those of smaller providers, who may not have the same access or capabilities.
The customer expresses that they miss Gorkana.

The client is concerned about the inability to isolate figures by territory, specifically UK figures versus global figures. They question why the four quarterly reports cannot be combined into a fiscal year report. There are also concerns about the inability to isolate UK circulation figures and the effort required to remove TV adverts from coverage.

The client is starting to get antsy about whether the contract is working as hard as it can for them. They are questioning the year-on-year increase and are coming at it from a finance perspective. The client is also concerned about potential double counting of clipping services and is considering whether to have individual markets manage their own clipping services.
The client is questioning the origin and rationale behind the formula used to calculate UK reach. They need a robust argument to support the formula.

Paula needs the end-of-year decision report for a senior meeting and added up the four quarter reports herself. The report was needed before the 24th of July for a board meeting. The client is questioning the year-on-year increase and is coming at it from a finance perspective. It's up to Paula to sort things out with Georgina. The client has the final decision.

Hannah mentions Elizabeth and Lily are expected to join the call. The RBU raised a query about the discrepancy between decision figures and UK figures. The UK client wants UK-specific reach figures. The UK PNG side and the European PG side have differing opinions. The European and UK sides will likely have a conversation, with a potential push to use global figures. The UK client wants the formula used. The UK team will want the UK figure. The client is questioning whether the current setup is double counting. The client is considering getting rid of one of the clipping services. There are 11 or 12 different territories, each potentially working out figures differently.

Paula needed the end-of-year decision report for a senior meeting. The report was originally planned to be sent on July 24th but was needed earlier for a board meeting. The earliest the figures could be done was July 24th. There will be frustration if the report couldn't be delivered tighter for her. Reports are usually wanted by the 10th of the next month. Paula will grill them on Friday about how the figure's been reached.

summary.text: This was a sales strategy meeting between Hannah Mitchell and Elizabeth Baker from the client side, and Thomas Anderson, Andrew Wilson, and Zara Ahmed from the vendor side, to prepare for a potentially challenging client meeting. The client team is seeking clarity on discrepancies between global and UK-specific reach figures for Oral-B, and the vendor team explained limitations in isolating UK circulation data within their platform, noting a formula currently used to calculate UK reach. The vendor team also addressed concerns about the inclusion of broadcast advertisements in coverage monitoring, offering to add exclusions based on provided examples and explaining how the platform can retroactively remove restricted content. The client team revealed the client is also evaluating alternative global providers, potentially due to concerns about cost and the value derived from the current contract. The vendor team emphasized the benefits of standardized metrics and reporting across all territories, a key reason the client initially chose their platform. The vendor team committed to investigating the origin of the UK reach formula. To prepare for the meeting, the client team requested the vendor side to send over an email by end of day summarizing their stance to promote alignment.
